title: S KOREA AIMS MEDALS AT OLYMPICS
description:
As the London Olympics approaches, the South Korean national shooting team aims for its best-ever Olympic performance at the upcoming event, hoping to win at least two gold medals.

13 athletes, including Olympic champion Jin Jong-oh, will compete across 12 Olympic categories in pistol, rifle, and shotgun.

Expectations are high for the national shooting team after South Korean shooters basked in their most successful Asian Games ever in Guangzhou two years ago by winning 13 gold medals.

CNCWorld has more.

With less than one month left until the London Olympics, the shooters were making final preparations at the newly-built Jincheon National Training Center, located some 90 kilometers south of Seoul.

Jin, making his third consecutive trip to the Olympics, will seek to defend his gold from 2008, while expecting to add another gold to his collection.

SOUNDBITE(KOREAN)JIN JONG-OH, KOREAN SHOOTING ATHLETE
"If I have a desire, it is to win the gold medal in the 10-meter event. I' ve been getting good results in the 10-meter competition, and it would feel greater to have the gold medal in the event."

Jin recently earned the 10-meter air pistol gold medal as well as the 50-meter pistol title at the shooting World Cup in Munich.

He vowed to live up to high anticipation among South Koreans for his second consecutive Olympic gold at the London Games.

SOUNDBITE(KOREAN)JIN JONG-OH, KOREAN SHOOTING ATHLETE
"Rather than being nervous, I feel a lot of pressure and that I am highly strung. But I appreciate the pressure because it' s the support I get from many people. To show my appreciation, I' ll repay with good performance at the Olympics."

Besides Jin, the country' s top medal hope in shooting, South Korea also eyes its first Olympic medal in women' s pistol events with Olympic hopeful Kim Jang-mi, who will compete in the women' s 10-meter air pistol and 25-meter pistol events.

Kim clinched the gold with a world record total of 796.9 in the women' s 25-meter pistol competition at the 2012 ISSF World Cup in London in April, raising the prospect of her winning a possible medal at the upcoming Olympic Games.

SOUNDBITE(KOREAN)KIM JANG-MI, KOREAN SHOOTING ATHLETE
"I' m now trying to feel mentally comfortable as much as possible, and I' m making preparations while hearing lots of Olympic advices from the coach."
The South Korean national team will leave for London around July 20.
